## Adding a new program

Use the plugin:

```
/pgas-new-program
```

The plugin's `/pgas-new-program` command detects this repo as a pgas
consumer, finds the `[pgas-plugin:*-registry]` markers in
`server/index.ts`, asks for the program name, and diff-and-confirms the
scaffold before writing.

## Cutting a release

Per `simodelne/pgas`/CONSUMER-VERSIONING-CONTRACT.md:

1. Bump `package.json` version.
2. If minor or major bump: run `/pgas:architecture-doc` to generate
   `audit/ARCHITECTURE-{{CONSUMER_NAME}}-v<X.Y.0>.md`.
3. Run `/pgas:5-fm-audit` — verify all five failure modes stay closed.
4. Open release PR; CI runs the same checks.
5. After merge, tag + push: `git tag vX.Y.Z && git push --tags`.
6. The `publish.yml` workflow publishes to GitHub Packages and
   nudges (warn-only) if the architecture doc is missing.

## Server bootstrap imports

`server/index.ts` imports every pgas-server construction primitive
(`SessionManager`, `ProgramRegistry`, `InMemoryEventBus`, `SqliteStore`,
the continuation consumers) through ONE stable path:
`@simodelne/pgas-server/api`.

That `/api` barrel (shipped in `@simodelne/pgas-server@1.9.0`, closing
[pgas#256](https://github.com/simodelne/pgas/issues/256)) is a
**side-effect-free** re-export surface: importing it loads class/function
definitions and returns — it never imports the engine's `"."` entry, so
it never calls `startTelemetry()` / `serve(...)` or opens a port.

Do **not** import from the bare `@simodelne/pgas-server` specifier: that
`"."` entry resolves to a runnable bootstrap with no `export` statements
(a process entry, not a library surface), so it both fails to typecheck
and would open a port at import time. The docblock at the top of
`server/index.ts` explains the rule, and `npx tsc --noEmit` fails loudly
if you reach for `"."`.

> Historical note: plugin v0.1.1 reached these symbols through deep
> internal subpaths (`@simodelne/pgas-server/bus/consumers/…js`) as a
> documented stopgap pending pgas#256. Plugin v0.2.0 retired that in
> favour of the barrel above.

